I was really looking forward to experiencing the food here. I'm not a snobby foodie by any means but I know what good food is. When I was in college I worked at a very fancy Florida country club with a french maitre'd in a tux. The kind of place serving chateaubriand and cherries jubilee and where I learned to make an authentic Caesar salad in a wooden bowl at the table. I brought a friend to GD's who has also been to many nice restaurants around the Western US. The menu ranged from fish to steak, lamb and chicken and was reasonably priced ($80-120) per meal. We went for the full monty 5 courses and then opted to try some special truffles and even a $50 glass of wine, both of which were a total waste of money. We ended up both being dissapointed overall with the food and atmosphere. I'm a local and still prefer cozier, clubby joints where the focus is on good food, not trendy who's who places.

3 course meal, would have left hungry had it not been for eating fries before hand. Bread and butter so bad. Bread was cold and like it came from the supermarket. Seemed such a nice place could splurge for quality bread. Butter was cold and unsalted. Foie gras was good. Scallops good. Quail was good. So for my meal only it was good but not spectacular, and I was barely full. Spouse got: - crab salad: ok - thai curry: ok - beef: ok All his dishes were not bad, but not that great. Really didn't like that they served second course when he was in the bathroom (even though they covered it to keep it warm). Should have just waited. Amuse was pea soup: ok. Petit fours: tasty like anything with sugar in it. 3.5 stars, probably wouldn't come again.

Wow! One of the best dinners I have ever had, if not the best. From the moment we stepped through the doors, we were greeted by the most exceptional service. I was so amazed by how the waiters paid attention to every single detail. They knew exactly what we needed before we even had time to ask. Besides the service, the food was out of this world amazing. My boyfriend and I both got the 4 course meal and shared everything. To start off, we had the seared foie gras with carmelized onions and apples. The foie gras was definitely one of my favorite dishes; it was rich and full of flavor and the onions gave it a nice kick. Next, we had the glazed oysters with osetra caviar, zucchini pearls, and lettuce cream. I'm not a fan of oysters, so I thought it was okay, but if you are an oyster fan, this is the dish for you. Then, we had the risotto with rock shrimp, dungeness crab, pumpkin, shimeji mushroom, and sage. The risotto was so creamy and I loved that there was a big piece of shrimp in every bite. This was also one of my favorites. After the risotto, we had the horseradish crusted salmon medallion with dilled cucumbers and mustard sauce. My boyfriend hates horseradish and even he thought the salmon was good! The salmon was cooked so perfectly that it melted in your mouth. We liked the mustard sauce so much that we used bread to sop it all up. Yummm. Then came the star of our meal: the roast maine lobster with potato puree, chanterelle mushrooms, edamame, and tarragon. The lobster was juicy and packed with flavor, and potato puree was smooth and creamy. I was so sad when it was gone because you only get a claw and a tail. You MUST get this dish. Our second favorite dish was the pan seared scallops with cannellini bean puree, garlic confit, tomato, and basil. The outside of the scallops had a nice crunchy sear, while the inside of the scallops were melt-in-your-mouth soft. One of the best scallops I have ever had. Also another dish that you must get. Then, we had the seared filet of beef with potato gnocchi, olive oil, swiss chard, and stilton butter. Th beef was okay, the outside was a little hard for my taste and it was a little bit too salty. There was also goat cheese (I think?), which I didn't like. My favorite part of the dish was the potato gnocchi. They were soft, chewy, flavorful balls of heaven. If the gnocchi was a dish by itself, I would definitely get that. Lastly, we had the herbed crusted loin of lamb with farrotto, medjool dates, rainbow carrots and green chermoula. I liked the lamb more than I liked the filet of beef. The lamb was cooked perfectly and the dates and carrots added a nice touch of sweetness to the herb-y crust. To top it all off, they brought over a cute little dish with different desserts. The desserts were okay, but the presentation was adorable. Definitely a one in a lifetime experience. You have to go try it for yourself to see.

Gary Danko has always been super high on my "must try" food places, but I was never inspired nor did I have a reason to actually come here. Well, my buddy told me that it was "the best dining experience [he] ever had," so that pretty much piqued my interest even more. And it just so happened that one of my long-time friends was turning 30, so the reason to come was taken care of. All I needed was a reservation on short notice...oh yes, I will CERTAINLY take a reservation at Sunday 10 PM on 2 weeks notice! First thing I noticed was how well-lit the interior was. Yeah I know ambiance is important, but I've been to enough fancy restaurants where I can barely see across the table to my dining partner. Well-lit enough, but not so bright as to take away from the atmosphere. Combined with the decor, I have to say it was the best ambiance of any restaurant I've been to (thus far, anyways). That said, I'm not quite sure about sitting on the same side as the person I'm with. Kinda weird to be staring at the tables in the middle, I feel like I'm spying on someone else's dining experience. :X Either way, menu is straightforward. 3/4/5-course menu, and you can choose any combination of appetizer/entree/cheese/dessert that you want (I wonder if anyone has actually done the 5-course dessert...if so, mad props to them!). Instead of doing the usual laundry list line-by-line, I'll do something different this time around. As usual, my standard rule applies...only get something you can't generally get somewhere else! ABSOLUTE MUST HAVES: Risotto with Gulf Shrimp, Dungeness Crab, Shimeji Mushrooms and Roasted Butternut Squash - Ok yeah, you can get risotto anywhere else. But risotto THIS good? Unquestionably the best risotto I've ever had in my life. Flavorful, yet super light. When I come here again, I'm getting this even though I already tried it...it is THAT good. Pan Seared Bass with Israeli Couscous, Pumpkin, Preserved Meyer Lemon and Sage - If you cannot decide what to get, start with this as it was inquestionably the best dish I had all night. Super flaky yet crispy with perfect texture, absolutely cooked to perfection. I'm still having dreams about how good it was. My only regret is that I didn't get two of these. PRETTY GOOD: Roasted Pork Tenderloin with Pork Belly, Eggplant-Pepper Marmalade, Pea Tendrils and Soy Mustard Glaze / Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Bacon Braised Endive and Cherries - I'll write on both of these at the same time. Pretty good, but not super memorable like the prior two dishes. Didn't help that these came out after the prior two dishes either. Honestly started to taste the same after a while, which probably wasn't good. Chocolate Mousse Cake - Hey it was a solid birthday cake, I can't complain about it. SHOULD'VE GOTTEN SOUFFLÉ: Flambéed Cherries with Mascarpone Filled Crèpes, Graham Cracker-Pecan Streusel and Port Ice Cream - Although it was cool to see the crepes being cooked in front of us, it was ok at best. Really wishing I had gotten the strawberry soufflé. What puts Gary Danko over the top is the top-level service. They know their stuff, are very friendly and accommodating, and and extremely knowledgeable about the menu, which helps when you have absolutely no idea what to get. And of course, thanks for that free pumpkin bread in the morning!

I was lucky enough to have my bf take me here for my birthday dinner! We arrived a few minutes before our 6 o'clock reservation. We were greeted as soon as we walked in, our coats were checked, and we were promptly brought to our table. We were seated in the smaller room to the left of the main dining area, which I actually didn't mind as the larger room was actually a little too loud when wanting to have a more intimate dining experience. The service was phenomenal, they pull the table out for you to get in, napkin placed on your lap for you, water glasses and wine glasses always being filled, bread being replenished (I had to ask my bf to not let me eat anymore so I wouldn't get full!) waiters periodically checking on you to make sure everything is great, opening of the bathroom door for you and at the end of the meal asking if we needed any transportation home. Finally, onto the food: I ordered 4 courses with the bf ordering 3, we of course shared everything! Appetizers: Seared fois gras with caramelized pears and onions- perfectly cooked, did not melt into a puddle of oil as soon as it was cut into Glazed oysters with osetra caviar- soooo good, creamy and seafood-y in a good way Seafood: Pan Seared scallops- they were the biggest juiciest scallops I've ever had, so fresh and sweet. My favorite dish of the night! Roast Maine lobster with potato puree- one tail and claw. As tasty as it was, my bf wished there was clarified butter to dip it in Entree: Roast quail stuffed with mushrooms and quinoa- very juicy and plump little bird! Every little bite was so flavorful and with all the stuffing, a surprisingly filling dish Seared filet of beef with potato gnocchi- cooked medium rare, it melts in your mouth. The gnocchi are heavenly little pillows that melt in your mouth Dessert: Trio of crème brûlée- vanilla, bourbon and olive oil. My fave was the olive oil as it was lemony, and the bf liked the bourbon. All three were fun to break into! Received a complimentary chocolate mousse and some petit fours for my bday that were all yummy! And the golden wrapped goodies to take home were pumpkin cheese cakes!

This is a must have dining experience; at least once! Delicious cuts and especially perfect for a special celebration. Reservations are a must so plan ahead because they book up!

Dinner for one The a la carte menu is only served at the bar( does not take reservations). If you would like to call in advance to reserve a table, you must at least order a 3-course ( start from $8X) set dinner. I arrived at 7pm on a weekday in January, and the bar was fully occupied. Luckily, I was seated within 20 minutes. My orders: Roast lobster with potato puree ( appetizer portion): perfect execution! Grand Marnier soufflé: The texture was perfect, crispy on top and fluffy in the middle. The orange sauce was a tad too acidic for my liking, but it's good after consuming a big meal. The gentleman who sat beside me generously offered me a bit of his chocolate soufflé, which also tasted very good. Service was excellent and oh how can I not love it when they spoil me with a lovely farewell gift and complimentary small plates between the courses. Total bill: $54 ( excluding tips)

It's unclear how this happened, but it took me almost 4 years to get here. But, it happened. And it was glorious. My husband made a reservation early, which conveniently was a week after I finished cutting weight for my weightlifting competition. By now you've read about the decor, the stunning flower arrangements in and around the restaurant, the amazing service, the little freebies you get after you're done with dinner, and the glorious food. So much food. Gary Danko's menu is absolutely a "choose your own destiny" adventure, and so for that night, my husband had the 3 course option whereas I selected the 4 course. #YOLO So. Like SportsCenter, let's do a recap of the Top 5 Plays of the Night by Gary Danko: 5. The Strawberry Souffle with Strawberry Sauce and Strawberry Sorbet: Easily on of the more elegant and lighter desserts I've had in awhile. After 3 courses, I was ready for something that wasn't overly rich and this fit the bill. 4. My second course was the Scallops, recommended to me by one of my good friends who said they were not to be missed. So, from one friend to the other, don't miss out on these, they're absolutely delicious and I loved the mushrooms that came with it. 3. Crispy eggs are one of my favorites, and Gary Danko nailed this one. The egg was fried beautifully, and like the scallops, came with absolutely beautiful mushrooms. The pancetta was a great addition and added a lot of texture with the crispiness of the egg. 2. DUCK. Don't wimp out and get beef like I almost did. Thankfully, I checked Yelp before going, and this was highly recommended. The duck was cooked beautifully, and the portion size was perfect for my appetite (and knowing that I had dessert coming!). 1. And of course. The cheese selection. It would be shameful to not rate this as the highlight of the night. Early on in our relationship, my husband would continually remind me that GD's cheese service was the best of all time. And, well, he was right. The cheeses we had were absolutely amazing. DO NOT miss this. The last thing I'll say about this is that GD is one of the more reasonably priced prix fixe menus I've experienced so far in SF. It's no surprise that reservations are hard to come by, and everything that night was completely on point, save the tourist who was wearing cargo shorts and the girl that was dressed for Hakkasan Las Vegas at the table across from us. Come on guys, it's Gary Danko, have some respect for the dress code and for your fellow diners. I would absolutely love to have the privilege of coming back here, if not just for that cheese course.

    Wow! One of the best dinners I have ever had, if not the best. From the moment we stepped through the doors, we were greeted by the most exceptional service. I was so amazed by how the waiters paid attention to every single detail. They knew exactly what we needed before we even had time to ask. Besides the service, the food was out of this world amazing. My boyfriend and I both got the 4 course meal and shared everything.

    To start off, we had the seared foie gras with carmelized onions and apples. The foie gras was definitely one of my favorite dishes; it was rich and full of flavor and the onions gave it a nice kick.

    Next, we had the glazed oysters with osetra caviar, zucchini pearls, and lettuce cream. I'm not a fan of oysters, so I thought it was okay, but if you are an oyster fan, this is the dish for you.

    Then, we had the risotto with rock shrimp, dungeness crab, pumpkin, shimeji mushroom, and sage. The risotto was so creamy and I loved that there was a big piece of shrimp in every bite. This was also one of my favorites.

    After the risotto, we had the horseradish crusted salmon medallion with dilled cucumbers and mustard sauce. My boyfriend hates horseradish and even he thought the salmon was good! The salmon was cooked so perfectly that it melted in your mouth. We liked the mustard sauce so much that we used bread to sop it all up. Yummm.

    Then came the star of our meal: the roast maine lobster with potato puree, chanterelle mushrooms, edamame, and tarragon. The lobster was juicy and packed with flavor, and potato puree was smooth and creamy. I was so sad when it was gone because you only get a claw and a tail. You MUST get this dish.

    Our second favorite dish was the pan seared scallops with cannellini bean puree, garlic confit, tomato, and basil. The outside of the scallops had a nice crunchy sear, while the inside of the scallops were melt-in-your-mouth soft. One of the best scallops I have ever had. Also another dish that you must get.

    Then, we had the seared filet of beef with potato gnocchi, olive oil, swiss chard, and stilton butter. Th beef was okay, the outside was a little hard for my taste and it was a little bit too salty. There was also goat cheese (I think?), which I didn't like. My favorite part of the dish was the potato gnocchi. They were soft, chewy, flavorful balls of heaven. If the gnocchi was a dish by itself, I would definitely get that.

    Lastly, we had the herbed crusted loin of lamb with farrotto, medjool dates, rainbow carrots and green chermoula. I liked the lamb more than I liked the filet of beef. The lamb was cooked perfectly and the dates and carrots added a nice touch of sweetness to the herb-y crust.

    To top it all off, they brought over a cute little dish with different desserts. The desserts were okay, but the presentation was adorable.

    Definitely a one in a lifetime experience. You have to go try it for yourself to see.

All I needed was a reservation on short notice...oh yes, I will CERTAINLY take a reservation at Sunday 10 PM on 2 weeks notice!

    First thing I noticed was how well-lit the interior was. Yeah I know ambiance is important, but I've been to enough fancy restaurants where I can barely see across the table to my dining partner. Well-lit enough, but not so bright as to take away from the atmosphere. Combined with the decor, I have to say it was the best ambiance of any restaurant I've been to (thus far, anyways). That said, I'm not quite sure about sitting on the same side as the person I'm with. Kinda weird to be staring at the tables in the middle, I feel like I'm spying on someone else's dining experience. :X

    Either way, menu is straightforward. 3/4/5-course menu, and you can choose any combination of appetizer/entree/cheese/dessert that you want (I wonder if anyone has actually done the 5-course dessert...if so, mad props to them!). Instead of doing the usual laundry list line-by-line, I'll do something different this time around. As usual, my standard rule applies...only get something you can't generally get somewhere else!

    ABSOLUTE MUST HAVES:
    Risotto with Gulf Shrimp, Dungeness Crab, Shimeji Mushrooms and Roasted Butternut Squash - Ok yeah, you can get risotto anywhere else. But risotto THIS good? Unquestionably the best risotto I've ever had in my life. Flavorful, yet super light. When I come here again, I'm getting this even though I already tried it...it is THAT good.
    Pan Seared Bass with Israeli Couscous, Pumpkin, Preserved Meyer Lemon and Sage - If you cannot decide what to get, start with this as it was inquestionably the best dish I had all night. Super flaky yet crispy with perfect texture, absolutely cooked to perfection. I'm still having dreams about how good it was. My only regret is that I didn't get two of these.

    PRETTY GOOD:
    Roasted Pork Tenderloin with Pork Belly, Eggplant-Pepper Marmalade, Pea Tendrils and Soy Mustard Glaze / Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Bacon Braised Endive and Cherries - I'll write on both of these at the same time. Pretty good, but not super memorable like the prior two dishes. Didn't help that these came out after the prior two dishes either. Honestly started to taste the same after a while, which probably wasn't good.
    Chocolate Mousse Cake - Hey it was a solid birthday cake, I can't complain about it.

    SHOULD'VE GOTTEN SOUFFLÉ:
    Flambéed Cherries with Mascarpone Filled Crèpes, Graham Cracker-Pecan Streusel and Port Ice Cream - Although it was cool to see the crepes being cooked in front of us, it was ok at best. Really wishing I had gotten the strawberry soufflé.

    What puts Gary Danko over the top is the top-level service. They know their stuff, are very friendly and accommodating, and and extremely knowledgeable about the menu, which helps when you have absolutely no idea what to get. And of course, thanks for that free pumpkin bread in the morning!

    See all photos from Alexander Y. for Gary Danko

    I was lucky enough to have my bf take me here for my birthday dinner! We arrived a few minutes before our 6 o'clock reservation. We were greeted as soon as we walked in, our coats were checked, and we were promptly brought to our table.

    We were seated in the smaller room to the left of the main dining area, which I actually didn't mind as the larger room was actually a little too loud when wanting to have a more intimate dining experience.

    The service was phenomenal, they pull the table out for you to get in, napkin placed on your lap for you, water glasses and wine glasses always being filled, bread being replenished (I had to ask my bf to not let me eat anymore so I wouldn't get full!) waiters periodically checking on you to make sure everything is great, opening of the bathroom door for you and at the end of the meal asking if we needed any transportation home.

    Finally, onto the food:
    I ordered 4 courses with the bf ordering 3, we of course shared everything!

    Appetizers:
    Seared fois gras with caramelized pears and onions- perfectly cooked, did not melt into a puddle of oil as soon as it was cut into

    Glazed oysters with osetra caviar- soooo good, creamy and seafood-y in a good way

    Seafood:
    Pan Seared scallops- they were the biggest juiciest scallops I've ever had, so fresh and sweet. My favorite dish of the night!

    Roast Maine lobster with potato puree- one tail and claw. As tasty as it was, my bf wished there was clarified butter to dip it in

    Entree:
    Roast quail stuffed with mushrooms and quinoa- very juicy and plump little bird! Every little bite was so flavorful and with all the stuffing, a surprisingly filling dish

    Seared filet of beef with potato gnocchi- cooked medium rare, it melts in your mouth. The gnocchi are heavenly little pillows that melt in your mouth

    Dessert:
    Trio of crème brûlée- vanilla, bourbon and olive oil. My fave was the olive oil as it was lemony, and the bf liked the bourbon. All three were fun to break into!

    Received a complimentary chocolate mousse and some petit fours for my bday that were all yummy!

    And the golden wrapped goodies to take home were pumpkin cheese cakes!

    ROTD 3/12/2015 and 2 other badges

    It's unclear how this happened, but it took me almost 4 years to get here. But, it happened. And it was glorious. My husband made a reservation early, which conveniently was a week after I finished cutting weight for my weightlifting competition.

    By now you've read about the decor, the stunning flower arrangements in and around the restaurant, the amazing service, the little freebies you get after you're done with dinner, and the glorious food. So much food. Gary Danko's menu is absolutely a "choose your own destiny" adventure, and so for that night, my husband had the 3 course option whereas I selected the 4 course.  #YOLO

    So. Like SportsCenter, let's do a recap of the Top 5 Plays of the Night by Gary Danko:

    5. The Strawberry Souffle with Strawberry Sauce and Strawberry Sorbet: Easily on of the more elegant and lighter desserts I've had in awhile. After 3 courses, I was ready for something that wasn't overly rich and this fit the bill.

    4. My second course was the Scallops, recommended to me by one of my good friends who said they were not to be missed.  So, from one friend to the other, don't miss out on these, they're absolutely delicious and I loved the mushrooms that came with it.

    3. Crispy eggs are one of my favorites, and Gary Danko nailed this one. The egg was fried beautifully, and like the scallops, came with absolutely beautiful mushrooms. The pancetta was a great addition and added a lot of texture with the crispiness of the egg.

    2. DUCK. Don't wimp out and get beef like I almost did. Thankfully, I checked Yelp before going, and this was highly recommended.  The duck was cooked beautifully, and the portion size was perfect for my appetite (and knowing that I had dessert coming!).

    1. And of course. The cheese selection. It would be shameful to not rate this as the highlight of the night. Early on in our relationship, my husband would continually remind me that GD's cheese service was the best of all time. And, well, he was right. The cheeses we had were absolutely amazing. DO NOT miss this.

    The last thing I'll say about this is that GD is one of the more reasonably priced prix fixe menus I've experienced so far in SF.  It's no surprise that reservations are hard to come by, and everything that night was completely on point, save the tourist who was wearing cargo shorts and the girl that was dressed for Hakkasan Las Vegas at the table across from us. Come on guys, it's Gary Danko, have some respect for the dress code and for your fellow diners.  I would absolutely love to have the privilege of coming back here, if not just for that cheese course.

    Gary Danko probably does not need me to add to its acclaim, but given my recent bittersweet move out of San Francisco to the burbs after almost 15 years as a city girl, coming here for my birthday seems extra appropriate in my own sentimentality.

    When I was broke in my early 20s living in San Francisco, Gary Danko was simply a name of luxury that I couldn't afford.  As I started to make more money, the ever-changing city made me chase the newest and coolest trends, often ignoring the classics.

    Last night at gary Danko I felt like a grown up.  Only grown ups get to eat like this: impeccable service from host to somm to valet; beautiful and elegant plating devoid of any froufrou fads; foie gras, scallops, creme brûlée prepared to textbook perfection.

    The elbow room was a bit tight, but that serendipitously gave us the opportunity to chat with a couple next to us.  They even gave us pineapple cakes to take home.

    Gary Danko makes me feel good about growing up.
